list.item:
Address the envelope to “The Honourable (official’s name), M.P.” The abbreviated form of the title, M.P.,  always comes at the end of the first line. After naming the official, add a second line spelling out their full title. Be sure to specify the name of the country over which they preside, as in, “Prime Minister of (name of country).” 

The completed address on the outside of your envelope should look something like this: “The Honourable William Clay, M.P/Prime Minister of Australia.”

If the official is distinguished by any other post-nominal identifiers, such as a province key like “B.C.” ( “British Columbia”),  be sure to list them right after “M.P.”{{greenbox:Tip: Use the more traditional phrase, “The Right Honourable” when referring to the prime minister of the U.K. or Canada in particular.}}
